                                  <mspace width="0.2em"/>
                                  <mfrac>
                                    <mrow>
                                      <mtext>90,700 J</mtext>
                                    </mrow>
                                    <mrow>
                                      <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
                                      <mtext>4040 g</mtext>
                                      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
                                      <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
                                      <mn>50.0</mn>
                                      <mspace width="0.2em"/>
                                      <mtext>°C</mtext>
                                      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
                                    </mrow>
                                  </mfrac>
                                  <mspace width="0.2em"/>
                                  <mo>=</mo>
                                  <mtext>0.449 J/g °C</mtext>
                                </mrow>
                              </annotation-xml>
                            </semantics>
                          </math>
                        </div>
                        <p id="fs-idm37197024">
                          Although the large pan is more massive than the small pan, since both are made of the same material, they both yield the same value for specific heat (for the material of construction, iron). Note that specific heat is measured in units of energy per temperature per mass and is an intensive property, being derived from a ratio of two extensive properties (heat and mass). The molar heat capacity, also an intensive property, is the heat capacity per mole of a particular substance and has units of J/mol °C (
                          <a
                            class="autogenerated-content"
                            href="#CNX_Chem_05_01_HeatCapacity"
                          >Figure 9.8</a>).
                        </p>
                        <div class="os-figure" id="CNX_Chem_05_01_HeatCapacity">
                          <figure
                            class="scaled-down"
                            data-id="CNX_Chem_05_01_HeatCapacity"
                          >
                            <span
                              data-alt="The picture shows two black metal frying pans sitting on a flat surface. The left pan is about half the size of the right pan."
                              data-type="media"
                              id="fs-idm67222368"
                            >
                              <img
                                alt="The picture shows two black metal frying pans sitting on a flat surface. The left pan is about half the size of the right pan."
                                data-media-type="image/jpeg"
                                id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                                src="/resources/28262012ba150fd2964e56b8379de4449ebe5e22"
                              >
                            </span>
                          </figure>
                          <div class="os-caption-container">
                            <span class="os-title-label">Figure</span>
                            <span class="os-number">9.8</span>
                            <span class="os-divider"></span>
                            <span class="os-divider"></span>
                            <span
                              class="os-caption"
                            >Because of its larger mass, a large frying pan has a larger heat capacity than a small frying pan. Because they are made of the same material, both frying pans have the same specific heat. (credit: Mark Blaser)</span>
                          </div>
                        </div>
                        <p id="fs-idm50153600">
                          water has a relatively high specific heat (about 4.2 J/g °C for the liquid and 2.09 J/g °C for the solid)); most metals have much lower specific heats (usually less than 1 J/g °C). The specific heat of a substance varies somewhat with temperature. However, this variation is usually small enough that we will treat specific heat as constant over the range of temperatures that will be considered in this chapter. Specific heats of some common substances are listed in
                          <a
                            class="autogenerated-content"
                            href="#fs-idm68801008"
                          >Table 9.1</a>.
                        </p>
