                        <p
                          id="fs-idm2064512"
                        >Note that the relationship between heat, specific heat, mass, and temperature change can be used to determine any of these quantities (not just heat) if the other three are known or can be deduced.</p>
                        <div data-type="example" id="fs-idm41581920">
                          <h3 class="os-title">
                            <span class="os-title-label">Example</span>
                            <span class="os-number">9.2</span>
                            <span class="os-divider"></span>
                          </h3>
                          <p id="fs-idm4867616">
                            <span data-type="title">Determining Other Quantities</span>
                            A piece of unknown metal weighs 348 g. When the metal piece absorbs 6.64 kJ of heat, its temperature increases from 22.4 °C to 43.6 °C. Determine the specific heat of this metal (which might provide a clue to its identity).
                          </p>
                          <p id="fs-idp15079712">
                            <span data-type="title">Solution</span>
                            Since mass, heat, and temperature change are known for this metal, we can determine its specific heat using the relationship:
                          </p>
                          <div data-type="equation" id="fs-idp21155408">
                            <math display="block">
                              <semantics>
                                <mrow>
                                  <mrow>
